  Admissions and Programs  PhD in Disability Studies  Meet Our Students      Meet Our Students  Our students come from diverse disciplines, backgrounds, and countries around the world.  Students enroll in our program for a variety of reasons and with a range of goals for when they graduate, including academic positions, disability policy and advocacy, and visual or performing arts.      What will you do with your Ph.D. in disability studies?           Denise Arnold   Design, develop and apply interactive technologies that support learning and promotes social integration of people and families living with autism         Valerie Barich   Advocacy at a community level for interdependent housing and employment            Suraiya Aktar Bably   Empower women with disabilities through computer literacy and technology            Caitlin Crabb   Research community-based services at a policy research organization            Sydney Erlikh   Impact national policy focused on art education and programs for individuals with developmental disabilities            Lily Diego-Johnson   Change perceptions of disability in mental health practices in many, many ways for consumers and practitioners            Fani Lee   Contribute to state policy changes for young adults with disabilities transitioning from high school to post-secondary setting            Michael J. McNicholas   Develop a research-based program that targets community-based services for U.S. military veterans in their home communities            Katherine Perez   Continue to be part of the Disability Rights Movement as an attorney, academic and activist            Mizanur Rahman   Become an influential social advocate in the field of employment of youth with disabilities            Helen Rottier   Lead dynamic and collaborative research that will enrich and elevate the lives of disabled individuals and communities            Kristen Salkas   Influence transportation provision and policy for people with disabilities and other minority identities            Elizabeth (liz) Anh Thomson   Ensure that the disability identity and disability social justice lens is appreciated and utilized in issues of diversity and inclusion            Washieka Tenieka Torres   Explore the way we look at food and food access for marginalized communities, and create equitable media            Chun-shan (Sandie) Yi   Teach disability and art at the college level, and produce artistic scholarly research about the intersection of disability and fashion            Victor Kuansong, Zhuang   Contribute to and shape current debates of inclusion in Singapore                Disability and Human Development    Back to main content           Admissions and Programs    Expand Admissions and Programs menu          Minor in Disability and Human Development    BS in Disability and Human Development    Expand BS in Disability and Human Development menu          What to Expect    Before You Apply    Applying    Expand Applying menu          Transferring from another UIC program      After You Apply      MS in Disability and Human Development    PhD in Disability Studies    Expand PhD in Disability Studies menu          What to Expect    Before You Apply    Applying    After You Apply    Faculty    Meet Our Students      Assistive Technology Certificate    Expand Assistive Technology Certificate menu          What to Expect    Applying    Faculty    Assistive Technology Certificate FAQ      Disability Ethics Certificate    Expand Disability Ethics Certificate menu          What to Expect    Applying        Institute on Disability and Human Development    Community Partners    Expand Community Partners menu          Bodies of Work      Research Centers, Clinics and Community Programs    Continuing Education and Community Training    News    Calendar    Directory    Contact              Follow Disability and Human Development      Facebook      Twitter      Instagram                         College of  Applied Health  Sciences